data.name: butSearchGaz.ToolTip
data.value: Use this button to invoke a dialog from which you can search the OS 1:50,000 gazetteer for place names and get corresponding grid references. Useful if you are entering a record without a GPS grid reference.

data.name: chkNewLocation.ToolTip
data.value: A convenience method for adding a new location to the locations gazetteer: if this box is checked with the Commit button is clicked then a new location entry is created with the specified name at the mid-point of the specified grid reference.

data.name: TreeView1.ToolTip
data.value: Select a taxon from this list to automatically populate the scientific and common name fields. If you select a scientific name which has non-scientific synonyms listed under it, then the first one of these will be used as the common name. If you select a non-scientific name from a synonym list then this will be used as the common name and if it has a parent which is a corresponding scientific name, then that will be used as the scientific name.

data.name: cboScientificName.ToolTip
data.value: You can type any part of a name in here and click the adjacent button to retrieve all taxa from the NBN taxon dictionary where where the name includes the string you type. Alternatively just specify the name you want to use - or select from the drop-down list.

data.name: cboCommonName.ToolTip
data.value: You can type any part of a name in here and click the adjacent button to retrieve all taxa from the NBN taxon dictionary where where name includes the string you type. Alternatively just specify the name you want to use - or select from the drop-down list.

data.name: txtAuthority.ToolTip
data.value: These fields are only displayed for information purposes. They idincate metadata stored against taxa in the NBN taxon dictionary. The most important one is the taxon group which is also saved to the Gilbert 21 convenience taxon dictionary.

data.name: radSpecifyBestFit.ToolTip
data.value: Use this option to specify the number of points the software should use to calculate the track in order to find the offset location. You may need to do this, for example, if you changed direction just before making the record.

data.name: butOffsetGR.ToolTip
data.value: This will calcuates a new grid reference from the original latitude and longitude recorded by the GPS by offsetting the specified distance and angle. The precision of the new grid reference matches that currently held against the record.
